"use strict";(self.webpackChunk_N_E=self.webpackChunk_N_E||[]).push([[52],{40052:function(e){e.exports=JSON.parse('[{"id":"q1","category":"Theory","question":"According to the Frontend Layer architecture, SSR achieves ~0.5s first meaningful paint while CSR takes ~3–4s. Why is SSR faster for first-time visitors?","options":["SSR pages are pre-cached at every CDN edge node before any user visits","SSR pre-renders complete HTML on the server so the browser displays content immediately, while CSR sends an empty shell and waits for the JavaScript bundle to download, parse, and execute before rendering anything","SSR eliminates all client-side JavaScript, so there is nothing to download","SSR uses HTTP/2 server push to pre-load assets alongside the initial HTML response"],"correct":1,"explanation":"The Frontend diagram documents SSR at ~0.5s vs CSR at ~3–4s first meaningful paint. SSR returns a fully rendered HTML document — the browser paints it instantly. CSR returns an empty <div id=\\"root\\"> and content only appears after the bundle downloads (~1s), parses (~0.5s), and React hydrates (~0.5s). The gap widens on slow mobile connections.","hint":"Focus on what the browser actually receives in each case — is it ready-to-render HTML or an empty container waiting for JavaScript?"},{"id":"q2","category":"Theory","question":"The Frontend architecture diagram shows a CDN layer with 200+ Points of Presence serving static assets. In the ISR (Incremental Static Regeneration) flow with `revalidate: 60`, what happens to the user who makes the very first request AFTER the 60-second window expires?","options":["They are blocked and shown a loading spinner while the server regenerates the page synchronously","They receive a 503 error until the CDN purges the stale cache","They receive the stale cached page immediately (stale-while-revalidate), while the server generates a fresh version in the background for the next visitor","The CDN automatically detects expiry and fetches a fresh page before delivering it"],"correct":2,"explanation":"ISR implements stale-while-revalidate: the current request always gets the cached version instantly — zero wait time — maintaining static-site performance. The origin generates a fresh page asynchronously. The next visitor gets the updated version. HTML files use `Cache-Control: no-cache` so the browser always checks freshness, but ISR background generation prevents any user from waiting for a regeneration.","hint":"ISR is designed so no user ever waits — think about what \'stale-while-revalidate\' means for the request that triggers regeneration."},{"id":"q3","category":"Practical","question":"Identify the critical security vulnerability in this post-login token handler:","code":"async function handleLoginSuccess(token: string) {\\n  // Persist JWT so user stays logged in across page refreshes\\n  localStorage.setItem(\'access_token\', token);\\n  window.location.href = \'/dashboard\';\\n}","codeLanguage":"typescript","options":["`window.location.href` causes a full page reload — use `router.push()` to avoid losing React state","The function is not wrapped in try/catch to handle QuotaExceededError from a full localStorage","Storing the JWT in localStorage exposes it to Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) — any JavaScript on the page, including injected malicious scripts via a compromised dependency, can call `localStorage.getItem(\'access_token\')` and exfiltrate the token","The function should verify the JWT signature client-side before storing it to prevent token forgery"],"correct":2,"explanation":"The Frontend Production Checklist explicitly states: \'Auth tokens in httpOnly cookies, not localStorage.\' localStorage has no access controls — any JS on the page reads it. One XSS vulnerability in your code or any third-party npm package, and every user\'s token is stolen. The fix: store access tokens in a module-level variable (lost on refresh = acceptable) and store refresh tokens in an httpOnly, Secure, SameSite=Strict cookie that JS cannot access.","hint":"Consider what JavaScript code running on the same origin can access. Think about the XSS attack — can a malicious script read localStorage?"},{"id":"q4","category":"Practical","question":"Your React app uses content-hashed bundles (e.g., `app.3f2c1a.js`). You deploy a new version — the CDN still serves the old HTML referencing `app.3f2c1a.js`, but that file has been deleted from the origin (replaced by `app.9b7d2e.js`). What does the user experience?","options":["React silently falls back to the previous bundle version — the old page loads without errors","React\'s error boundary catches the missing chunk and renders a fallback UI automatically","The browser requests `app.3f2c1a.js`, gets a 404 — React throws a ChunkLoadError causing a blank screen or broken hydration until the user hard-refreshes to get the new HTML","The CDN detects the hash mismatch via its integrity check and fetches the new HTML before responding"],"correct":2,"explanation":"This is a cache invalidation race condition at deployment time. The old HTML references a chunk URL that no longer exists — the 404 triggers an unhandled ChunkLoadError. Mitigations from the spec: (1) configure HTML files with `Cache-Control: no-cache` so browsers always fetch the latest HTML, (2) keep old chunk files alive for at least 24h after deploy, (3) add a global `ChunkLoadError` handler that calls `window.location.reload()` to auto-recover.","hint":"If the server returns 404 for the JavaScript chunk the browser needs, can React finish mounting the application?"},{"id":"q5","category":"Theory","question":"According to the Frontend Layer Production Checklist, what are the two performance targets that directly guard against bundle bloat and measure overall page quality?","options":["Bundle size < 500KB initial JS; Lighthouse CI score > 70","Bundle size < 1MB initial JS; Lighthouse CI score > 80","Bundle size < 200KB initial JS; Lighthouse CI score > 90 — these guard Time-to-Interactive on mid-range mobile devices and directly affect Core Web Vitals LCP and INP","Bundle size < 100KB initial JS; Lighthouse CI score > 95"],"correct":2,"explanation":"The Production Checklist specifies \'Bundle size < 200KB initial JS\' and \'Lighthouse CI score > 90.\' On a mid-range Android device on a 4G connection, 200KB of compressed JS still takes ~1s to parse and execute. Exceeding this degrades INP (Interaction to Next Paint) and LCP (Largest Contentful Paint) — both Core Web Vitals that directly affect Google Search ranking. Lighthouse CI in the pipeline enforces this automatically on every deploy.","hint":"Look for both a byte budget and a composite quality score in the Frontend Production Checklist."}]')}}]);